    <!-- SECTION 1 -->
    <h2>What Anabolic Resistance Actually Is</h2>

    <p>Most men over 40 who train consistently and eat reasonably well notice the same thing eventually: the results are slower than they used to be. Recovery takes longer. Muscle comes harder. Strength gains plateau. The instinctive explanation is age — "I'm just not 25 anymore." And while age is part of the picture, it's not the whole story.</p>

    <p>The more precise explanation is anabolic resistance — a specific, measurable decline in your muscle tissue's sensitivity to the protein and exercise signals that trigger muscle building. It's not that your muscles can't respond. It's that the signal isn't getting through at the dose it used to.</p>

    <p>Think of it like a radio losing reception. The broadcast is still happening — protein is still arriving, exercise is still creating the stimulus. But the receiver needs a stronger signal to pick it up. Anabolic resistance is that loss of reception. And the fix isn't changing the broadcast — it's amplifying the signal.</p>

