    <!-- SECTION 4 — THE THREE STRATEGIES -->
    <h2>Three Ways to Overcome Anabolic Resistance</h2>

    <div class="strategy-grid">
      <div class="strategy-card">
        <div class="sc-num">1</div>
        <h4>Hit 30–40g of Complete Protein Per Meal</h4>
        <p>This is the non-negotiable. Below 30g from complete protein sources, most men over 40 won't reliably clear the leucine threshold. Every meal needs a high-quality protein anchor — not a side serving. See <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/50g-protein-breakfast-men-over-40/">how to build a 40–50g breakfast</a> that clears this threshold at the first meal of the day.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="strategy-card">
        <div class="sc-num">2</div>
        <h4>Distribute Across 3–4 Meals — Not 1–2</h4>
        <p>Each meal triggers an independent MPS episode lasting 4–5 hours. Missing a meal's threshold doesn't get compensated by eating more at dinner — that window is closed. Even distribution across the day means 3–4 threshold-clearing events daily. <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-pacing-strategy-men-over-40/">The pacing strategy</a> explains exactly how to structure this.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="strategy-card">
        <div class="sc-num">3</div>
        <h4>Maintain Consistent Resistance Training</h4>
        <p>Training preserves mTOR pathway sensitivity — making your muscles more responsive to the protein signal. Men who train regularly show significantly less severe anabolic resistance than sedentary peers at the same age. Resistance training and adequate protein aren't alternative strategies — they're multiplicative. Both together work far better than either alone.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warning-box">
      <div class="warning-label">What Doesn't Work</div>
      <p>Spreading 120g of daily protein across 6 small meals of 20g each does not overcome anabolic resistance — it multiplies the missed-threshold problem. Six meals at 20g each means six meals below the leucine threshold. Six missed MPS windows. More frequent eating is not the fix. Higher per-meal dose is the fix.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 5 — TRACKING CONNECTION -->
    <h2>Why You Can't Track Leucine — And Why That's Fine</h2>

    <p>Leucine content isn't displayed on nutrition labels. You cannot practically track it the way you track protein grams. But here's the thing: you don't need to.</p>

    <p>The leucine threshold translates cleanly to protein grams from complete animal protein sources. Hit 30–40g of complete protein per meal — from chicken, beef, fish, eggs, dairy, or whey — and you will be in the leucine threshold range. The protein gram target is the practical proxy for the leucine threshold. Track protein, and leucine takes care of itself.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p><strong>This is why per-meal tracking matters more than daily total tracking.</strong> A man who hits 120g daily but eats it in two large meals has cleared the threshold twice. A man who hits 120g across four meals of 30g each has cleared it four times. Same daily number. Completely different anabolic outcome. <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/is-100g-protein-enough-200lb-man/">The 100g post shows this math</a> applied to a real bodyweight.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The practical implication: you aren't just tracking grams — you're tracking anabolic trigger events. Every meal that clears 30g of complete protein is a window where muscle repair and growth can happen. Every meal that misses it is a missed window. Over weeks and months, the difference between consistently clearing the threshold and consistently missing it by 10–15g per meal is the difference between maintaining muscle and slowly losing it.</p>

