    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is anabolic resistance after 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Anabolic resistance is the age-related decline in muscle tissue's sensitivity to protein and exercise signals. After 40, the mTOR pathway — the molecular switch that triggers muscle protein synthesis — responds less efficiently to the same protein dose that would have built muscle at 25. Men over 40 need more leucine per meal — approximately 3.5–4g versus 2–2.5g for younger adults — to generate the same muscle-building response.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How much leucine do men over 40 need per meal to overcome anabolic resistance?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Research suggests approximately 3.5–4g of leucine per meal to reliably trigger muscle protein synthesis in men over 40 — compared to 2–2.5g for younger adults. In practical terms, this means 30–40g of complete protein per meal from high-quality sources like chicken, beef, fish, eggs, or dairy. You don't need to track leucine directly — adequate complete protein grams per meal is the reliable proxy.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Can anabolic resistance be reversed?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Anabolic resistance cannot be fully reversed — it's a physiological reality of aging muscle tissue. But it can be significantly overcome through consistent resistance training (which preserves mTOR sensitivity), higher per-meal protein intake (30–40g to clear the elevated leucine threshold), and even protein distribution across 3–4 meals per day. These strategies don't reverse the resistance — they raise the signal high enough to overcome it.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What foods have the most leucine for men over 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The highest-leucine foods are whey protein (~10–11% leucine by weight), chicken breast, tuna, cottage cheese, Greek yogurt, eggs, and beef. To hit the 3.5–4g threshold per meal, aim for 30–40g of complete protein from these sources. Combinations work well — 3 eggs plus a cup of Greek yogurt hits ~3.6g of leucine and clears the threshold at breakfast without any supplement.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Why do men over 40 need more protein than younger men?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Anabolic resistance is the primary reason. After 40, muscle tissue responds less efficiently to protein signals — the mTOR pathway requires a higher leucine concentration per meal to activate. This is why research supports 1.2–1.6g of protein per kilogram of bodyweight daily for men over 40, compared to 0.8g/kg for younger adults — and why per-meal dosing of 30–40g matters as much as the daily total.</div>
      </div>
